[normal]How should the Highways Agency be reformed[bold]&#xa0;[bold]to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private[bold] sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?[bold]Suffolk Chamber of Commerce 
[normal]has concerns 
[normal]about the Highways Agency
[normal]’s current culture and performance which
[normal] arise from the fact that it is remote and disconnected from businesses and lo
[normal]cal communities with regard to planning and managing the strategic road network.
[normal]Although we believe that the 
[normal]Agency needs strong management and 
[normal]perhaps
[normal] greater independence from Government
[normal], and 
[normal]more involvement by private finance
[normal], some of the Chamber’s re
[normal]cent experiences suggest that unless the Agency achieves major cultural change in respect of its relationship with the private sector then it will continue to fail to capture the latent benefits of private sector partnership working
[normal]Two recent examples ill
[normal]ustrate this point. 
[normal]First, the Agency recently 
[normal]drew together
[normal] a group of strategic partners in connection with a number of challenges around the A14 and,
[normal] not least, the congestion that 
[normal]frequently 
[normal]occurs on or close to the Orwell crossing just outside 
[normal]Ipswich
[normal]. The Agency convened a summit with MPs and senior representatives from the local authorities but made no attempt to reach the Chamber or any other business voice organisations. An opportunity was lost to secure the input from some of the major user
[normal]s of the A14 which links the 
[normal]Port
[normal] of 
[normal]Felixstowe
[normal] to the Midlands and therefore acts as an economic driver for 
[normal]Suffolk
[normal], 
[normal]East Anglia
[normal] and indeed UK plc.
[normal]Second, the Agency 
[normal]has very recently
[normal] consult
[normal]ed
[normal] on proposed improvements to the A14 between Huntingdon and 
[normal]C
[normal]ambridge
[normal] and on proposals to toll the new route. 
[normal]Suffolk Chamber 
[normal]of Commerce 
[normal]support
[normal]s the
[normal] improvements 
[normal]but at the same time has strong
[normal] concerns
[normal] 
[normal]at Government proposals to partly fund those improvements through tolling.
[normal]The
[normal] public consultation exercise, led
[normal] for Government by the Highways Agency and regarding the proposed improvements and tolling arrangements, was launched on 9 September 
[normal]and c
[normal]onclude
[normal]d
[normal] on 13 October 2013.
[normal]The Chamber
[normal]’s concerns 
[normal]about the consultation process 
[normal]are based on a number of specific c
[normal]ircumstances which again illustrate the Agency’s disconnectedness from businesses and communities
[normal]. In particular:
[normal]All of this suggest
[normal]ed
[normal] to us that Government 
[normal]through the Agency had
[normal] already concluded that the 
[normal]improvements and proposed tolling are not a major issue
[normal] for business
[normal] in 
[normal]Suffolk
[normal] and other counties outside Cambridgeshire. This is not correct of course and seems to us to sit uncomfortably with Government’s wish to secure a wide base of financial contribu
[normal]tions towards the project, both up-front from local partners and in the longer term through tolling.
[normal]Whatever structural changes are made the Highways Agency will not become 
[normal]“the world’s leading highway operator”
[normal] unless it works collaboratively and positiv
[normal]ely with businesses and local communities.
